snippet.textDisplay: XFS should rock.  I've been using XigmaNAS as my nearline photography NAS for quite some time (including before the name change).  RAID 1+0, all in software.  Upside is that adding disks (in pairs) is very straight forward and I'd have to double fault a mirror set to have to resort to backups.  Downside is that I consume more drives (And slots) than a RAID Z2 which should survive a double fault.  XFS can also be enabled with journaling.

snippet.textDisplay:
You would think, at some point, Linus would just pay the piper instead of trying to make a trailer park server for a professional brick and motor company which these days are finite.

Its not like I don't love the channel, but these guys still think it's ok to spray thermal paste in a globbed line like there are no repercussions.

They had unlimited resources to build a top 1 percent machine and cheaped out on every integral component to get you there; all while ignoring parameters and the "why" which exists to achieve such.

They are their own problem 100percent of the time and every video has essentially turned into not helping users, but rather, telling viewers exactly how not to do it to reach the desired results.

That's a technological failure on many aspects but hey only views matter to them.

That's most likely why a brick and motor company, worth more than a billion dollars and is on the cutting edge of data protection involving banks and ATMs pays me well beyond six figures to be their computer engineer and why Linus lives off merch and advertising.

You get what you pay for, every time: Good advice is included.
